Problem Statement¶

Pneumonia is an infection in one or both lungs. Bacteria, viruses, and fungi cause it. The infection causes inflammation in the air sacs in your lungs, which are called alveoli.

Now to detection Pneumonia we need to detect Inflammation of the lungs. In this project, youre challenged to build an algorithm to detect a visual signal for pneumonia in medical images. Specifically, your algorithm needs to automatically locate lung opacities on chest radiographs.

Business Domain Value Automating Pneumonia screening in chest radiographs, providing affected area details through bounding box. Assist physicians to make better clinical decisions or even replace human judgement in certain functional areas of healthcare (eg, radiology).

Project objective In this capstone project, the goal is to build a pneumonia detection system, to locate the position of inflammation in an image.

def process_dicom_data(data_df, data_path):
    for var in vars:
        data_df[var] = None
    image_names = os.listdir(PATH+data_path)
    for i, img_name in tqdm(enumerate(image_names)):
        imagePath = os.path.join(PATH,data_path,img_name)
        data_row_img_data = dcm.read_file(imagePath)
        idx = (data_df['patientId']==data_row_img_data.PatientID)
        data_df.loc[idx,'Modality'] = data_row_img_data.Modality
        data_df.loc[idx,'PatientAge'] = pd.to_numeric(data_row_img_data.PatientAge)
        data_df.loc[idx,'PatientSex'] = data_row_img_data.PatientSex
        data_df.loc[idx,'BodyPartExamined'] = data_row_img_data.BodyPartExamined
        data_df.loc[idx,'ViewPosition'] = data_row_img_data.ViewPosition
        data_df.loc[idx,'ConversionType'] = data_row_img_data.ConversionType
        data_df.loc[idx,'Rows'] = data_row_img_data.Rows
        data_df.loc[idx,'Columns'] = data_row_img_data.Columns  
        data_df.loc[idx,'PixelSpacing'] = str.format("{:4.3f}",data_row_img_data.PixelSpacing[0])

EDA Notes¶














Files provided¶
    

  1. Detailed Class File that contains Patient ID and Classification if the patient has Lung Opacity, Normal or Not normal condution

     a.This file has 30227 entries 
    

    2. 

  2. Train Labels File that has Patient ID, pixel co-ordinates that serve as bounding box for patients that suffer lung opacity issue and the same is confirmed by last column ie Target

     a. The target column has two value 0 for patients with no lung opacity issues and 1 for patients with lung opacity issues
 b. This file too has 30227 entries
    

    3. 



Dataframe Processing¶
Data in both files mentioned above were consolidated to create a new Pandas DataFrame called train_df
train_df now has 30227 entries with 7 columns


Observations from EDA¶
From the graphs and Value Counts it is evident to note that there is class imbalance



No Lung Opacity / Not Normal    11821
Lung Opacity                     9555
Normal                           8851




If we consider Normal and No Lung Opacity as one class, then the class distribution is as follows:



No Lung Opacity       20672
With Lung Opacity     9555





The train_df.info output shows that there are no null values in the dataset


Of the total 30227 records we have :



26684 unique patient records
3543 records are duplicated
all duplicated records belong to class - Patient with Lung Opacity
Data types : float64(4), int64(1), object(2)




Observations from Sample Image¶


All images are in DCM format, had to install pydicom to read the images
All images come with Metadata
All images are of resolution 1024 X 1024
pydicom library provides the pixel array















Gender distribution for positive lung opacity¶
    

  1. Higher number of males reported for lung opacity
    2. 

  2. Lung opacity is seen to be more frequent in patients of age group between 50 years to 70 years
    3. 
















Dealing with Class imbalance¶














There are 2 approaches being explored :


    

  • Downsample the majority class to match the minority class and create the CNN
    • 

  • Upsample the minority class through mini batch SMOTE
    • 
















Approach 1 : Downsample¶

from tqdm import tqdm
IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH = 224,224
ORG_HEIGHT, ORG_WIDTH =1024,1024
import cv2
from tensorflow.keras.applications.mobilenet import preprocess_input
train_masks = np.zeros((int(final_taining_df.shape[0]), IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH,3), dtype=np.uint8)
train_images = np.zeros((int(final_taining_df.shape[0]), IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH, 3), dtype=np.uint8)
for index in tqdm(range(final_taining_df.shape[0])):
          image_id = final_taining_df["patientId"][index]
          fname = str(image_id)
          image_path = train_images_path %fname
          info2 = pydicom.read_file(image_path)
          image = info2.pixel_array
          if len(image.shape) != 3 or image.shape[2] != 3:
              image = np.stack((image,) * 3, -1)
              img = cv2.resize(image, dsize=(IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH), interpolation=cv2.INTER_CUBIC)
              train_images[index]= img
          Target = final_taining_df["Target"][index]
          if Target == 1:
              x = int(final_taining_df['x'][index])
              y = int(final_taining_df['y'][index])
              w = int(final_taining_df['width'][index])
              h = int(final_taining_df['height'][index])
              x1 = int(int(x * IMAGE_WIDTH)/ORG_WIDTH)
              x2 = int(int((x+w) * IMAGE_WIDTH)/ORG_WIDTH)
              y1 = int(int(y * IMAGE_HEIGHT)/ORG_HEIGHT)
              y2 = int(int((y+h) * IMAGE_HEIGHT)/ORG_HEIGHT)
              mask_img=np.zeros((IMAGE_HEIGHT, IMAGE_WIDTH,3),np.uint8)
              img_mod= cv2.rectangle(mask_img,(x1,x2),(x2,y2),(255,0,0),3)
              train_masks[index] = img_mod

def display_img(sample_image,pred_mask):

In [80]:



    


def dice_coefficient(y_true, y_pred):
    numerator = 2 * tf.reduce_sum(y_true * y_pred)
    denominator = tf.reduce_sum(y_true + y_pred)

    return numerator / (denominator + tf.keras.backend.epsilon())



    













In [81]:



    


def loss(y_true, y_pred):
    return binary_crossentropy(y_true, y_pred) - tf.math.log(dice_coefficient(y_true, y_pred) + tf.keras.backend.epsilon())

In [87]:



    


def dice_coefficient(y_true, y_pred):
    numerator = 2 * tf.reduce_sum(y_true * y_pred)
    denominator = tf.reduce_sum(y_true + y_pred)
    return numerator / (denominator + tf.keras.backend.epsilon())



    













In [88]:



    


def loss(y_true, y_pred):
    return binary_crossentropy(y_true, y_pred) - tf.math.log(dice_coefficient(y_true, y_pred) + tf.keras.backend.epsilon())
